article.headline: California 66, Arizona State 62 (OT)
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- When California was in big trouble, Ayinde Ubaka took over and the Bears escaped with a 66-62 overtime victory over Arizona State Saturday night. The senior point guard scored eight of his 14 points in overtime, including two 3-pointers. "Coach told me to start being more aggressive," Ubaka said. "They put three people on the top to take me away, and he said you still have to shoot. He said they're going to do that every game and you still have to be aggressive." Cal led most of the game but freshman Christian Polk made an off-balance 3-pointer under tight defense with 3.9 seconds left that tied it at 55 and forced the overtime. Polk also hit a long 3-pointer to beat Iowa earlier this season. "Christian made a miraculous shot," said first-year coach Herb Sendek, who said he saw good improvement and great effort from his young team despite the loss. "Early in his career he's shown an amazing capacity to do that, but then we quickly fell behind in overtime and just never could get that thing turned around again." Ubaka, 4-for-9 on 3-pointers, made the two 3s early in the extra session to put Cal up for good 61-55 with 1:41 left. His two free throws with 13.3 seconds left sealed the victory. "Ubaka's a real good player," Polk said. "He's a senior. He knows what he's doing out there. Good players make big plays, and that's what he did." Sendek knew how good Ubaka is because his North Carolina State team beat California last season in the first round of the NCAA tournament. "He's clearly among the best point guards in the country," the Arizona State coach said. The Bears were 12-for-28 from the 3-point range. Freshman Ryan Anderson led Cal (9-5, 1-1 Pac-10) with 18 points. Eric Vierneisel added 14 and Omar Wilkes 10. It was the first win for the Bears in their three games without center DeVon Hardin, out with a stress fracture in his left foot. "A great effort," Cal coach Ben Braun said. "That's probably one of the best efforts in terms of stepping up when our backs were so-called against the wall. They (the Sun Devils) had everything on their side. They had momentum, they had everything and Ayinde Ubaka wouldn't let his team go down tonight." Polk and Antwi Atuahene scored 14 apiece for Arizona State (6-7, 0-2). Jeff Pendergraph added 11 points and Jerren Shipp 10 for the Sun Devils. Shipp missed two free throws that could have cut the lead to one with 23.6 seconds to go. The Bears made five 3-pointers in the first 10:20 of the second half and led 49-45 on Anderson's inside basket with 5:23 to play. Atauhene's 3-pointer trigged a 7-0 spurt that gave Arizona State a 52-49 on Shipp's rebound basket with 3:03 to play. Cal cut it to 52-51 on Anderson's baseline drive, then regained the lead 53-52 on a breakaway layup by Wilkes. The Bears led 55-52 on Anderson's inside basket with one minute to play. Wilkes and Anderson both were fouled on their baskets and missed free throws that would have made three-point plays. Sendek called three timeouts in the final minute of regulation, the last with 10 seconds to go, then Polk sank the 3-pointer that forced the overtime. California led 22-21 after an ugly first half that ended with Ubaka's 3-pointer at the buzzer. Both teams shot 35 percent and combined for 18 turnovers in the first half, 10 by Arizona State.
